# Verify Every Edition Claim Against Its Evidence

## Question

"SUPER important to get the information correct." Build a verification pass that runs after extraction, before the edition is preserved: an independent pi verifier checks each prose claim — headline, framing, whyItMatters, digests, and every marked take — against the observations it cites. A claim its evidence doesn't support gets flagged (v1: a visible unverified mark in the rendered paper, not silently killed), and takes must carry their synthesized mark plus evidence refs or they don't print.

Prototype on real editions: run the verifier over the last few days' output, show Joel what it catches (false claims, overreach, orphaned takes), and let him calibrate the dial — flag, kill, or eventually gate the build. Whether it becomes a hard publish gate stays in the map's fog until calibration data exists.

Resolved when a live edition renders verifier verdicts and Joel has set the strictness dial against real catches.

**Status 2026-07-12**: both halves live — sidecar verdicts (wiki `7fcba10`) AND rendered flags (wiki `3d8ba61`): overreach/unsupported/unverifiable get quiet small-caps marks on the exact sentences, verifier note on hover, tally line in the folio; supported renders nothing. Today's paper shows its own audit (16 overreach, 3 unverifiable rendered). Remaining: Joel sets the flag/kill/gate dial; verifier-as-chief's-instrument moves to the newsroom ticket.
